            <p>Phalaenopsis orchids were first discovered in the 17th century by Dutch botanist Georg Rumphius and gained European popularity in the 19th century, eventually becoming the most widely cultivated orchids worldwide. Their name means "moth-like" in Greek, referring to their butterfly-shaped flowers.</p>
            <p>Today, they remain the most popular houseplant orchid globally.</p>
